  "title": "Accelerated Inorganic Materials Design with Generative AI Agents",
  "experiments_summary": "The study implements MatAgent, a framework combining LLMs (GPT-4o and o3-mini) with external tools for iterative materials discovery. The methodology involves: (1) LLM-driven Planning stage where the model selects from four tools (short-term memory, long-term memory, periodic table, knowledge base) with explicit reasoning; (2) LLM-driven Proposition stage where compositions are proposed based on retrieved tool information and previous feedback; (3) Crystal Structure Estimation using a diffusion model (DiffCSP) trained on the MP-60 dataset to generate 3D structures from compositions, producing five structures for formula units 1-4 per composition; (4) Property Evaluation using iComFormer (GNN-based transformer) trained on formation energy to assess structures and provide feedback. The MP-60 dataset was curated from Materials Project containing 48,323 structures with ≤60 atoms per unit cell, split 6:2:2 for training/validation/test. Experiments targeted specific formation energies (-3.8, -3.5, -3.0, -2.5, -1.6 eV/atom based on dataset quantiles) with 20 independent runs of 15 iterations each, starting from randomly sampled compositions. Comparative experiments included tool-free LLM variants and MatterGen (diffusion model with classifier-free guidance). Evaluation metrics included success rate (within ±0.25 eV/atom of target), compositional validity (SMACT), uniqueness, novelty (absence from MP-20 training set), and V.U.N. score. Additional experiments tested constrained generation using natural language prompts (excluding toxic elements, actinides, or restricting to non-metals) and knowledge-informed initialization methods (LLM-based and retriever-based using contrastive learning with T5 encoder). Tool contribution was analyzed individually, and reasoning interpretability was assessed using SciBERT embeddings with t-SNE visualization and k-means clustering."
